ick, undertaking charitable work, and hosting community events, all the while continuing to record her reactions to her new world in her writing and artwork.First published in 1950, A Gentlewoman in Upper Canada is a classic work of early pioneering literature. This new, significantly expanded edition includes many of Langton's original illustrations and reveals Langton's views on writing, art, and women's social and familial roles in nineteenth-century Europe and Canada. In her extensive introduction, Barbara Williams contextualizes Langton's life and work and reflects on them in light of current scholarship in life writing, art history, and early emigrant, cultural, and social history. This is the definitive edition of Anne Langton's important text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArt, Canadiany19th century. 0aArtistszCanadavBiography. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezOntario. 0aWomen immigrantszOntariovBiography. 0aWomen pioneerszOntariovBiography. 0aWomenzOntarioxSocial conditionsy19th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268816240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442688162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442688162.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK